```

## Bibliography Management

### Chapter-Specific References

Background chapters typically have many citations. Use `references.bib` in chapter2 directory for chapter-specific references:

```bibtex
@article{author2023approach,
  author = {Author, A. and Coauthor, B.},
  title = {Novel Approach for Edge Computing},
  journal = {IEEE Transactions on Cloud Computing},
  year = {2023},
  volume = {11},
  number = {2},
  pages = {234--249}
}
```

### Citation Best Practices

**Density**: Background chapters are citation-heavy
- Technical background: Cite textbooks, foundational papers
- Literature review: Cite every approach discussed
- Gap analysis: Cite works that exhibit the limitations

**Quality over Quantity**:
- Prefer peer-reviewed journals/conferences over arXiv
- Use most recent version of evolving standards
- Cite seminal works for foundational concepts
- Cite recent surveys for field overview

**Proper Attribution**:
```latex
✅ Smith et al. [X] first proposed this approach in 2015. Later work by Jones [Y] extended it to handle [scenario].

❌ This approach was proposed [X, Y, Z]. (Unclear who did what)
❌ There are many papers on this topic [list of 20 citations]. (Cite selectively, not exhaustively)
```

